# 2026-06-13 23:27:30.673621
+The MVP is working perfectly. Now, I want to upgrade this app for public web deployment. It must remain free and require NO user accounts, but users should only see their own data. I also need export/import, categorization, and image support.
+
+Please implement the following architecture strictly using the correct Aider edit format (bare filename on line 1, ``` on line 2):
+
+1. Anonymous Sessions (No-Login Privacy):
+- Update `prisma/schema.prisma`: Add `sessionId String` to the `Document` model.
+- Frontend: Create a utility or hook that generates a unique UUID on first visit, saves it to `localStorage` (e.g., 'notion_session_id'), and attaches it to all API requests via an `x-session-id` header.
+- API (`/api/documents/...`): Update all GET, POST, PATCH, and DELETE routes to read the `x-session-id` header and filter/mutate ONLY the documents belonging to that sessionId.
+
+2. Export & Import (JSON):
+- Format: JSON (to perfectly preserve TipTap content and nested parent-child structures).
+- UI: Add "Export Backup" and "Import Backup" buttons at the bottom of the Sidebar.
+- Export Logic: Fetch all documents for the current sessionId and trigger a download of `notion-backup.json`.
+- Import Logic: Parse an uploaded JSON file and bulk-create/upsert the documents into the database, assigning them the current browser's `sessionId`.
+
+3. Categorization:
+- Update `prisma/schema.prisma`: Add `category String?` to the `Document` model.
+- UI: Add a simple way in the UI (maybe a dropdown or input below the title) to assign a category to a document. Update the `DocumentTree` or Sidebar to group documents by their categories.
+
+4. Image Support (Base64):
+- Assume I will install `@tiptap/extension-image@2`.
+- Update `Editor.tsx`: Add the Image extension to the TipTap configuration.
+- Add an image upload button to the editor toolbar. When a user selects an image, convert it to a Base64 string and insert it into the TipTap editor. (This avoids external cloud storage costs for a free app).
+
+Execute these changes step-by-step: first the Prisma schema, then the API routes, and finally the UI components.

